{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17537280","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17537280"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:15:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:15:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16018"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16018","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16018"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.52,0.1,0.15,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8709"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108491"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8709","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8709"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16018"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90878"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"3496"},{"type":"tags","id":"4327"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"9594"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20837"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32768"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40482"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43601"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108491","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108491"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 21-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic at 29 weeks gestation with a three-week history of intensely pruritic blisters. The rash began on her abdomen around her umbilicus and has spread to involve her arms and legs. She has depression and takes only sertraline and pregnancy vitamins. Her medications have been unchanged during her pregnancy, and she has not started any new lotions or changed any cleaning products. She is a current smoker.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There are tense vesicles and bullae on an erythematous base over her abdomen, arms, and legs. Some areas show urticarial plaques.  She wants clear confirmation of the cause of the rash as she is concerned about the affect on her baby. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate investigation to confirm the diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Skin prick testing","Skin biopsy","Patch testing","Serum tryptase level","Serum anti-nuclear antibodies"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with clinical features highly suggestive of pemphigoid gestationis, a rare autoimmune blistering disease of pregnancy. The characteristic presentation begins in the second or third trimester with a red rash periumbilically, and it can develop into intensely pruritic vesicles and bullae on the rest of the body.  Diagnosis can be clinically, or by skin biopsy for confirmation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESkin biopsy \u003C/strong\u003Eby direct immunofluorescence of perilesional skin is the gold standard diagnostic test for pemphigoid gestationis if required. In some typical cases, clinical diagnosis is sufficient however if clarity is required, then biopsy and blood tests are performed. Biopsy reveals linear C3 and IgG deposits along the basement membrane zone, which is pathognomonic for the condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerum anti-nuclear antibodies\u003C/strong\u003E testing would not be helpful in diagnosing pemphigoid gestationis. While autoantibodies are involved in the pathogenesis, they are specifically directed against the basement membrane zone, not nuclear antigens.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPatch testing\u003C/strong\u003E is used to diagnose allergic contact dermatitis by identifying specific allergens that cause delayed hypersensitivity reactions. It would not be helpful in diagnosing an autoimmune blistering disease and is unlikely in this case where there has been no change to her environment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerum tryptase\u003C/strong\u003E levels are elevated in mastocytosis and acute allergic reactions. While pemphigoid gestationis can have urticarial features, tryptase measurement would not assist in diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESkin prick testing\u003C/strong\u003E is used to identify immediate hypersensitivity reactions in conditions such as urticaria or atopy. It would not be useful in diagnosing an autoimmune blistering condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPemphigoid gestationis requires prompt recognition and treatment to prevent complications for both mother and fetus such as premature delivery, small-for-gestational-age babies and a newborn with a blistering rash . The condition typically responds to systemic corticosteroids, and patients should be monitored closely as the disease can flare during the lead up to delivery and postpartum. There is also an increased risk of similar eruptions with subsequent pregnancies or oral contraceptive use.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Direct immunofluorescence showing linear C3 and IgG deposits at the basement membrane zone is diagnostic for pemphigoid gestationis.","Pemphigoid gestationis typically presents in the second or third trimester with intensely pruritic vesiculobullous eruptions.","Skin biopsy with immunofluorescence is essential to differentiate pemphigoid gestationis from other pregnancy-related dermatoses."],"references":["Parfene CG, Bohiltea RE, Mihai BM, Grigoriu C, Margaritescu I, Chirita AD, Zugravu CA and Pelinescu\u2011Onciul D. Influence of pemphigoid gestationis on pregnancy outcome: A case report and review of the literature. Experimental and Therapeutic Medicine. 2023. Available at: https://www.spandidos-publications.com/10.3892/etm.2021.10945","Ngan V, Stanway A, Mitchell G. Pemphigoid gestationis. DermNet NZ. 2021. Available at: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/pemphigoid-gestationis"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90878"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16018"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90878","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90878"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-11T18:05:06+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-11T18:07:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8709"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108491"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":